Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Treating "Not Given" values for column Rating

In[26]:
# Plots the distribution for column "Rating"
sns.histplot(data=df,x='rating',stat='density')
plt.show()
In[27]:
# Get a copy of the dataset to perform the changes and mantain the original dataset for future reference
df_treated = df.copy()
In[28]:
# Transforms "Not given" values in NaN to use fillna function further on
df_treated['rating'] = df_treated['rating'].replace('Not given', np.nan)

# Uses fillna function to fill NaN values with the mode of the column, since it is a string
df_treated['rating'] = df_treated['rating'].fillna(df_treated.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].transform(lambda x: x.mode()[0] if not x.mode().empty else None))

# Plots column "Rating" new distribution

Observations:

By using the info() function, it is possible to observe that there are no missing values in the dataset, and the isnull() function confirms it. However, the "rating" column contains "Not given" entries, which make up 38% of the data. These entries are not missing values per se, but they should be treated to improve the results of the analysis.

To improve the analysis, the "Not given" ratings were replaced with the most common (mode) rating for each restaurant. Thus, assuming that a restaurant would likely receive the most frequent rating from its historical data.

The distribution of the columns remained unchanged after this data transformation, indicating that the inference is valid. However, 30 entries remained not rated after the transformation. Since 30 rows is a small number considering the size of the dataset, they were removed.

The modified dataset is saved as df_treated to preserve the original dataset for future reference.

In[70]:
# Plots a linear correlation matrix for each one of the cuisine types in the list

cuisine_type_list = ['Mexican', 'Indian', 'Chinese', 'Italian']

for cuisine in cuisine_type_list:
  selected_cuisine_type = df_treated[df_treated['cuisine_type'] == cuisine]
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
  sns.heatmap(selected_cuisine_type.loc[:, ['cost_of_the_order', 'rating', 'total_time']].corr(),annot=True,cmap='Spectral',vmin=-1,vmax=1)
  plt.title(f'Correlation Matrix for {cuisine} Cuisine')
  plt.show()
  • The correlation matrix for the cuisine types do not show a linear correlation between cost of the order and rating. So, we will try to perform a non linear correlation.
  • The correlation matrix for the cuisine types show a medium negative linear correlation (-0.24) between total time and rating in Mexican cuisine. Which means orders which take the longest to get delivered tend to have worse ratings.
  • The contrary seems to be true for Indian cuisine. Although the correlation is weak, there is a 0.16 positive correlation between total time of preparation and delivery of an order and the rating the order receives.
In[71]:
# Plots a non linear correlation matrix (with Spearman method) for each one of the cuisine types in the list

cuisine_type_list = ['Mexican', 'Indian', 'Chinese', 'Italian']

for cuisine in cuisine_type_list:
  selected_cuisine_type = df_treated[df_treated['cuisine_type'] == cuisine]
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
  sns.heatmap(selected_cuisine_type.loc[:, ['cost_of_the_order', 'rating']].corr(method='spearman'),annot=True,cmap='Spectral',vmin=-1,vmax=1)
  plt.title(f'Correlation Matrix for {cuisine} Cuisine')
  plt.show()
  • The correlation matrix for the cuisine types show a negative non linear correlation (-0.19) between cost of the order and rating in Mexican cuisine. Which means orders which have the higher prices tend to have worse ratings.
  • The contrary seems to be true for Indian cuisine. Although the correlation is not strong, there is a 0.17 positive correlation between cost of the order and the rating the order receives.
  • The rest of the cuisines analyzed don't show any relevant non linear correlations.

Final observations:

  • There is not a strong relationship between general ratings and cost of the order, total time of delivery and day of the week.
  • However, there is relevant relationship between cost of the order and rating and total time of delivery and rating in Indian and Mexican cuisines.
  • Although the correlations are not strong, orders with higher prices and higher total time of delivery tend to have worse ratings in Mexican Cuisine.
  • Although the correlations are not strong and it is contrary to intuition, orders with higher prices and higher total time of delivery tend to have better ratings in Indian Cuisine.

In[86]:
# Excludes rows with not given ratings from the dataset
df_rating_num = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy()
# Transforms rating into a float data type
df_rating_num['rating'] = df_rating_num['rating'].astype('float')

# Creates a list of unique values on restaurants which have more than 50 ratings and the average rating is freater than 4
df_rating_num.groupby('restaurant_name').filter(lambda x: x['rating'].count() > 50 and x['rating'].mean() > 4)['restaurant_name'].unique()

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[87]:
# Creates a net revenue column using conditional functions to calculate the net revenue
df_treated['net_revenue'] = np.where(df_treated['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, df_treated['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25, 0) + np.where((df_treated['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (df_treated['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20), df_treated['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15, 0)
df_treated['net_revenue'].sum()

np.float64(6069.882)

The net revenue generated is 6069.88 dollars.

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

Conclusions:

The demand is highly concentrated regarding cuisine type, restaurants and on weekends:

  1. 80% of orders is concentrated in three cuisine types: American, Japanese and Italian. Also, Chinese, Mexican and Indian cuisine types seem to be potential market for growth.
  2. Approximately, 50% of orders is concentrated in the top 10 restaurants.
  • There are some characteristics in common between the top 10 most frequent restaurants: the order costs under 35 dollars and total time of delivery tends to be under 60 minutes.
  1. 80% of orders is concentrated on the Weekends:
  • Even between the top ten most frequent customers, only one of them has placed orders on weekdays
  • Also, there is tendency of higher delivery time during weekdays when compared to weekends in general and between all cuisine types

There is no concentration of orders in customers, which can be a good thing, since we are trying to reach the maximum number of customers as possible. On the other hand, the absolute number of orders per customers is still low (the highest number of orders by customer is 13).

Contrary to intuition, there are no relationship between general rating and other features of the dataset. However, when we deep dive on cuisine types, we see that:

  1. In Mexican cuisine, there is a medium negative linear correlation between total time of delivery and ratings, as well as a weak non linear correlation between cost of the order and rating.
  2. Contrary to intuition, in Indian Cuisine, there is weak positive correlation between rating and cost of the order (non linear) and rating and total time of delivery (linear).

Although we are not talking about strong correlations, it is important to note that, given the goal of the analysis and the fact that Indian and Mexican Cuisines seem to be potential markets for growth. Thete tips can help to raise demand and get better customer experience on there cuisine types.

Recommendations:

  1. At the same time, we should focus on the three most frequent cuisine types (American, Chinese and Italian) and in the three cuisine types which show more potential for maket growth (Mexican, Chinese and Indian). We could plan promotional offers to get even higher demand on those segments.
  2. Improve demand on weekdays, by offering promotional offers to most frequent customers. Thus, improving customer experience and loyalty.
  3. However, it is necessary to work on lowering delivery time during the week days. For that, further analysis should be made to understand the specific problems in delivery logistics on weekdays, since the mean delivery time is higher than on weekends, even though there is less demand.
  4. Logistics data (specially location and time) could be gathered to build a machine learning capable of predicting demand per neighborhood and different times of the day to lower delivery time.
  5. There is a significant percentage (38%) of orders not rated. Rating should be encourage with incentives to better understand customer experience. Also, there is an opportunity to gather text reviews and perform text analysis to deep dive on this theme.
